Horace will teach his friend Hirpinus his own philosophy. ‘Little is enough for life, enjoy the present fleeting moment with no thought of distant dangers, no greed for useless wealth. Youth quickly flies, and old age comes. All is change. How useless then to vex our souls with endless aims and efforts.'

Quinctius Hirpinus, apparently the friend to whom Epist. 1, 16 is addressed, is not further known. He seems to have been ambitious for wealth, but not averse to pleasures. The date of composition is proba- bly fixed as 26-25 B.C. by the mention of the bellicosus Cantaber v. 1. Metre, 68. .
